UE20CS934 – Time Series Forecasting (TSF)¶

ESA - Model Questions - Set 1¶

Section - B¶

Analytics firm wants to forecast the average spending of customers for the month of Oct 2020. For this, firm has gathered a closing stock price data for the period of Feb 2019 to Sept 2020.

a) Read the dataset. What are the number of rows and no. of cols & types of variables? (2 mark)

b) Convert the data into time series (3 marks)

c) Check for defects in the data such as missing values, null, etc. (2 mark)

d) Visualize the time series using relevant plots. (3 mark)

e) Decompose the time series and check for components of time series. (4 marks)

f) Perform dicky fuller test to check the stationarity? What other actions will you take if series is non-stationary? (3+2 marks)

g) Plot Auto Correlation and Partial Auto Correlation function? What is your inference from these plots? (3+3 marks)

h) Split dataset into train and test sets. Use last two months of data for testing. (5 marks)

i) Fit ARIMA model and observe the RMSE and MAPE values of the model for test data. (10 marks)

b) Convert the data into time series¶

In [2]:
import pandas as pd

# Read the dataset
data = pd.read_csv("data_set.csv")

# Convert the 'Date' column to datetime format and set the frequency
data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date'], dayfirst=True)
data.set_index('Date', inplace=True)
data = data.asfreq('D')  # 'D' stands for daily frequency

# Display the first few rows to verify

e) Decompose the time series and check for components of time series¶

In [5]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

# Decompose using multiplicative model
decomposition = seasonal_decompose(data, model='multiplicative')

# Plot the decomposition
decomposition.plot()
plt.show()
  • Trend: The trend component shows a steady increase from around 100 to approximately 500 over the observed period. This indicates a general upward movement in the data.
  • Seasonal: The seasonal component exhibits a consistent up-and-down pattern, suggesting regular fluctuations that repeat over a specific period.
  • Residual: The residual component remains relatively stable and close to zero, indicating that the model has effectively captured the trend and seasonal patterns, leaving minimal unexplained variance.

f) Perform Dickey-Fuller test to check the stationarity¶

In [6]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

adf_result = adfuller(data.dropna())
print(f'ADF Statistic: {adf_result[0]}')
print(f'p-value: {adf_result[1]}')

if adf_result[1] > 0.05:
    print("Series is non-stationary, differencing required.")
else:
    print("Series is stationary.")

ADF Statistic: -0.30908265623618103
p-value: 0.9242080692970707
Series is non-stationary, differencing required.
In [7]:
# Apply differencing
data_diff = data['Avg spending'].diff().dropna()
In [8]:
# Re-check stationarity
adf_result_diff = adfuller(data_diff)
print(f'ADF Statistic after differencing: {adf_result_diff[0]}')
print(f'p-value after differencing: {adf_result_diff[1]}')

if adf_result_diff[1] > 0.05:
    print("Series is non-stationary, differencing required.")
else:
    print("Series is stationary.")

ADF Statistic after differencing: -6.731902702457794
p-value after differencing: 3.2798705231972727e-09
Series is stationary.

In [9]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf

# Plot ACF and PACF
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plot_acf(data_diff, lags=30)
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plot_pacf(data_diff, lags=30, method='ywm')
plt.show()

  • From the ACF plot, the significant spike at lag 1 suggests q = 1.

i) Fit ARIMA model and observe RMSE and MAPE values for test data¶

In [11]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
from sklearn.metrics import root_mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_percentage_error

# Fit the ARIMA model
model = ARIMA(train['Avg spending'], order=(1, 1, 1))
model_fit = model.fit()

# Make predictions
predictions = model_fit.forecast(steps=len(test))
In [12]:
# Calculate RMSE and MAPE
rmse = root_mean_squared_error(test['Avg spending'], predictions)
mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(test['Avg spending'], predictions)

print(f'RMSE: {rmse}')
print(f'MAPE: {mape}')

RMSE: 55.45769961775811
MAPE: 0.07627183452255018
  • RMSE of 55.46 suggests that, on average, the models predictions deviate from the actual values by about 55.46 units.
  • A MAPE of 0.076 (or 7.63%): Generally, a MAPE below 10% is considered very good, indicating high accuracy.
In [13]:
# Plot the predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(train.index, train['Avg spending'], label='Train')
plt.plot(test.index, test['Avg spending'], label='Test')
plt.plot(test.index, predictions, label='Predictions', color='red')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Average Spending')
plt.title('ARIMA Model Predictions')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

a) Fit Exponential Smoothing Model and Observe Residuals, RMSE, and MAPE¶

In [14]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing
from sklearn.metrics import root_mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_percentage_error
In [15]:
# Fit the model
model = ExponentialSmoothing(train['Avg spending'], trend='add', seasonal=None, seasonal_periods=12)
model_fit = model.fit()

# Make predictions
predictions = model_fit.forecast(steps=len(test))
In [16]:
# Calculate RMSE and MAPE
rmse = root_mean_squared_error(test['Avg spending'], predictions)

print(f'MAPE: {mape}')
